The top runs continuously and meets with the upper receiver and extends slightly after the front sight. But it is available with fixed sight, flip sights or not sights.It has a mid-length gas operating system, so propellant gases are caught in a tube near the muzzle, the tube guides it back to the bolt and then catches in another tube on the bolt. When the gas is caught, it drives the bolt back. This delays recoil until the projectile has left the bore. Mid-length means that the gas is caught after a medium distance in the barrel, so less pressure is used to push the bolt back (compared to the short-length gas system).Features include a chrome lined bore, a vertical fore-grip, a MagPul buttstock that’s lightweight and adjustable, a cold hammer forged barrel, so a machine carefully carved the grooves in the bore. title: For Sale:  Historically Significant Colt .38 Revolver Presented to Medal of Honor Winner 1912 90% plus original condition
postcontent: For sale I have a high condition colt High Polish “oil finish” with fire blue small parts .38 Army Special manufactured in 1912. This 106 year old revolver remains in excellent condition retaining 95% of its original colt High Polish finish and the majority of its fire blue finish on small parts. This pistol is of historical significance as it purportedly Belonged to a Philippine insurrection medal of honor winner by the name of George Weed Wallace. There is a date engraved on the left side of June 7th 1912 which is reported to be the date he was promoted to LT. Col. and based on that  I’m assuming this was a gift for that promotion from friends or fellow company members and his initials of G.W.W. Are engraved on the butt bottom. While I have no way to definitively prove it was his except for the fact it was bought directly from the family it makes sense as the dates match up as far as when he lived and served in the military as he was awarded the Medal of Honor for gallantry in March 1900 and retired in 1919 from the military. Also this would have been nearly identical to the Colt model 1892 he carried during the Philippine insurrection so it would also make sense that this Type of arm would have been purchased for him upon his promotion. I currently have it displayed as shown below on a plexiglass stand backed by framed information on him and a copy of his citation for the medal of honor. Regardless of its previous owner this is still a very high condition 106 year old colt revolver that is extremely collectible and very desirable in the early colt High Polish finish with fire blued parts. The bore and cylinders are also mint and are a 10 out of 10. As you can see from the photos this revolver displays excellently. Will ship to any FFL or C&R holder in the lower 48. PayPal payment preferred if shipping is required. I have many more pictures I can either text or email to Interested parties. This revolver would benefit greatly from more research to find this american hero’s official military records. If that can be done you are talking about an extremely valuable revolver.
